{
  "doc_id": "55197",
  "text": "An alternative to organic probes for detection of cell activity is the recent development of a number of biosensors with numerous genetic constructions mostly related to the GFP protein family [CITATION_1] (Table 1) . This approach includes a vector transfection step of genetically encoded FRET biosensor(s) [CITATION_2] . Biosensor expression offers many possibilities to study molecular mechanisms in living cells including calcium, PKA, and ERK activities through FLIM-FRET experiments [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . With the development of lifetime imaging systems and new fluorescent proteins, simultaneous use of two FLIM-FRET biosensors within one sample is allowed [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . The biosensor strategy may bypass difficulties like probe penetration and autofluorescence in plants or microalgae [CITATION_7] . In addition, photoactivation-induced specific expression of biosensors in a group of cells, in cells, and in subcellular compartments offers a new perspective in cell biology studies [CITATION_8] . In the context of oocyte development, photoactivation of a subpopulation of microtubule subunits contributed to understanding of the comprehensive dynamics of microtubules within the mouse egg spindle [CITATION_9] .",
